english:
  title: Eulogy for Portrait of Park In-seok, Former Minister of Household Affairs, Hoegok Recluse
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven bestowed upon him the spirit of courage, and thus was born one of extraordinary character—our Park of Gyerim. In his youth, he harbored the ambition to heal the world, admiring the virtue of Zhuge Liang and Wang Jing. Most especially did he love the study of history, recounting the affairs of Han and Tang as if he had witnessed them yesterday. His prose captured the essence of Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan. He possessed exquisite knowledge of the principles of all things, and in matters of food and medicine, his skill was flawless. In archery and polo, he excelled beyond even the seasoned generals. Yet these were merely the gifts he chose not to conceal—what lay hidden within, only heaven knows.

    Fleeing the tumult of troubled times, he journeyed south and settled in Hoegok of Jukju, taking the name "Recluse of Hoegok." There he dwelt for more than thirty years. When Lord Jin-kang assumed power, hearing of the Gentleman's renown, he summoned him to the capital with great urgency. First he was placed in the Secretariat, then swiftly advanced. Within less than a decade, he soared to the highest ranks. Yet the world still lamented that he never became Prime Minister.

    The Gentleman's name was In-seok, his courtesy name Soo-san. He was the son of Yu-hwa, a celebrated minister of old. Long after his passing, I visited the home of his son, the Court Official, and beheld his portrait, painted by his old friend Li Sa. Moved by memory of our past friendship, tears fell unbidden. I humbly bow twice and offer this eulogy to be inscribed upon his portrait's frame:

    When heaven and earth lie shrouded in darkness,
    The great dragon rests in shallow waters.
    When the world grows clear and the Way opens wide,
    The graceful phoenix comes forth to dance.

    Is it dragon or phoenix?
    Appearance and concealment—each has its moment.
    Beholding this image left behind,
    The true form stands revealed here.

    Upon his head, the black hat rises proud;
    About his shoulders, the crane-feathered robe.
    Though the painter loved to render the extraordinary,
    And clothed him thus in sage's garb and recluse's visage,
    Yet the bone and frame cannot be hidden—
    Behold the countenance of one who would redeem the age and order all under heaven.

    Men see only the surface,
    And know not what is true.
    By this eulogy I reveal
    The essence that lies within.

    Who inscribed this praise?
    The recluse bears the name Lee.
  footnotes:
    - 'Gyerim (鷄林): An ancient name for Korea, often used poetically to refer to the Korean kingdoms.'
    - 'Zhuge Liang and Wang Jing: Celebrated historical figures known for their wisdom and service to their rulers—Park is compared to their virtue.'
    - 'Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan: Tang Dynasty literary masters whose prose style emphasized clarity and moral purpose.'
    - 'Hoegok of Jukju: Jukju (竹州) was an ancient Korean place name; Hoegok refers to a valley of cypress trees where Park retired.'
    - 'The eight ranks (八座): The highest administrative positions in the Korean bureaucracy.'
    - The epilogue's ambiguity about whether Lee was painter or author creates an intentional mystery, characteristic of classical Korean literary practice.
